story.title: Fatal Consequences - Episode 3
story.storyDescription: Jo-Jo awakens, trapped in the wreckage of her car, covered in blood. The last 48 hours of her life are a blank, and the dead man beside her . . . is a total stranger.

messages.text: 48 hours later, Jo-Jo is wearing stolen scrubs as she sneaks back to the diner to retrieve the USB.
She slips the cross around her neck as Arlo enters the kitchen.
Jesus, Jo! You look like hell!
Don‚Äôt sugarcoat it.
What happened?
I was in an accident.
You need to go home. Get some rest‚Ä¶
Arlo, you‚Äôve been great to me. I mean it. But I have to move on‚Äî
Permanently.
This wasn‚Äôt an accident, was it?
I can‚Äôt say any more.
Someone stalking you?
That‚Äôs one way to look at it.
Call the cops.
They can‚Äôt help me.
He‚Äôs in law enforcement?
I didn‚Äôt say that.
You don‚Äôt have to. Seen it too many times. Okay, wait here.
No, I really have to get moving.
Five minutes. I‚Äôll get your pay.
Okay, thanks. I‚Äôll grab my things.
Jo-Jo gets the change of clothes she keeps her locker.
As she‚Äôs putting them on in the ladies‚Äô room, she discovers the bump on her shoulder.
What the? Shit!
Jo-Jo pulls a Swiss Army knife from her bag and, gritting her teeth, makes an incision.
She removes the GPS chip and examines it.
Government issue. Damn!
Jo-Jo, you all right in there?
Jo-Jo walks out into the diner.
Yeah, I‚Äôm fine.
As she heads toward the register, she surreptitiously slips the GPS into the jacket of a long-haul trucker.
Here, take this.
That‚Äôs way too much, Arlo. There must be six hundred bucks here.
Don‚Äôt argue. You‚Äôre gonna need it. And take this, too.
A gun?
Do you know how to use it?
Yes.
She hides her sigh. If he only knew.
Arlo hugs her.
Okay, hit the road.
I don‚Äôt know how to thank you.
Just take care of yourself.
In the parking lot, Jo-Jo scans for a car she can hotwire.
Going somewhere, Miss Avery?
Detective, how did you‚Äî
Wait a minute, the GPS. Who are you working for?
Does it matter?
Of course it matters.
Let‚Äôs just say ‚Äúthe good guys.‚Äù
Somehow, I can‚Äôt picture you in a white hat.
No, I don‚Äôt imagine you can, but it‚Äôs the truth.
Why should I believe you?
Quinn steps closer. He brushes a stray hair from Jo-Jo‚Äôs face.
His touch feels extremely intimate.
I won‚Äôt try to convince you. You‚Äôll have to just trust what you feel.
I‚Äôm not sure I can.
Why not?
Because you‚Äôre attracted to me.
There‚Äôs no point denying it. I am.
But I haven‚Äôt let that interfere with my judgment.
If it hasn‚Äôt already, it will.
Why do you say that?
Because I‚Äôm attracted to you too. That changes the equation.
Why do I get the feeling that you‚Äôre a very good actress?
I see you don‚Äôt have any reason to believe me, either.
Jo-Jo shrugs.
I guess you‚Äôll have to trust how you feel too.
What do your instincts tell you?
I‚Ä¶Look, Jo-Jo, just give me the recording.
I can bring you in. Keep you safe.
I don‚Äôt think I can do that. My radar hasn‚Äôt been working too well lately.
Look what happened with Forrester.
But you were working with him to discredit Leighton.
Yes, I suppose I was. But Leighton‚Äôs no saint.
No but at least his politics have never been for sale.
True.
Why‚Äôd you get involved?
I‚Äôve done some research on you. This isn‚Äôt your usual gig.
Too many dollars and not enough sense.
I don‚Äôt follow.
They offered me double my usual fee.
Look, it was going be my last job. I‚Äôm getting out of the business.
I should‚Äôve known it was too good to be true.
Who was Forrester working for?
He never said. For all I know, Leighton set the whole thing up himself ‚Äî the sick bastard.
Leighton may be into some kinky stuff behind closed doors, but he‚Äôs not stupid.
Why film yourself in a compromising position?
Yeah, I‚Äôm grasping at straws. Has to be a political opponent, I guess.
So, what happened with Forrester?
He was hired to get the goods, and then kill me‚Ä¶
But I didn‚Äôt shoot him.
I know. We found his gun. It hadn‚Äôt been fired.
But you said‚Ä¶
I‚Äôm sorry. I didn‚Äôt want to lie to you, but I had to find out.
What? The color of my hat?
If you don‚Äôt believe anything else, believe this‚Äî
I have a good feeling about you.
Down in my gut, something about you feels right.
What the hell is that supposed to mean?
That keeping you safe is more important to me than you know.
Than even I understand.
On sudden impulse, Jo-Jo reaches up and kisses Quinn.
The mutual attraction is undeniable.
I want to believe you.
Quinn leans in to kiss her again. Jo-Jo cold-cocks him with the gun.
She looks down at his unconscious body.
But I can‚Äôt take the chance.
Jo-Jo rifles through Quinn‚Äôs pockets. She locates his cell and checks the call log.
It‚Äôs blank.
She memorizes his number, stuffs the phone back in Quinn‚Äôs pocket, and takes off.
After she disappears into the night, Quinn slowly regains consciousness.
Jo-Jo? Son of a bitch!
Quinn gets his phone and punches in Dante‚Äôs contact number.
What‚Äôs up?
She‚Äôs gone.
How?
She played me.
Ouch.
You don‚Äôt know the half of it.
Now what?
Backup tracker should be operational, but only for a few hours‚Äî
I slipped it into the boots she kept in her locker. She was wearing them when I saw her.
Any luck finding the recording?
I didn‚Äôt get a chance to grab it, but I‚Äôm pretty sure it‚Äôs concealed in her pendant ‚Äî a gold cross.
She didn‚Äôt have one at the hospital.
No, she had to come back here to get it.
It‚Äôs the only thing she‚Äôs wearing that wasn‚Äôt in her locker.
Any clue who hired Forrester?
She didn‚Äôt know, but she said he‚Äôd planned to eliminate her.
He told her it was part of his deal.
Shit.
I‚Äôll phone it in and wrap operations here.
Okay, keep me in the loop.
Will do.
Quinn disconnects the call.
Back at his office, Dante slams his phone on his desk.
Damn it to hell!
